{
  "texts": [
    "In the following, we provide a high-level description of how this conversion is done:• Each generated 𝑇 (𝑤 𝑡) begins by reporting the window's length (𝜏 seconds) and the approximate time of the day (in the format hh:mm am/pm).",
    "The first was found useful to provide a temporal context to the LLM since 𝜏 is usually shorter than the typical duration of an ADL; The second was found useful for the LLM to exploit correlations between common ADLs and the time of the day in which they are typically executed (e.g., preparing dinner, preparing lunch).",
    "• After reporting the temporal context, 𝑇 (𝑤 𝑡) describes what happened in the home during 𝑤 𝑡 from the subject's perspective (e.g., \"the subject opened the fridge\").",
    "This choice, rather than considering a sensor's perspective as done in other works [45] (e.g., \"the magnetic sensor on the fridge was activated\"), leverages the LLM implicit knowledge of how humans perform activities.",
    "Indeed, subject-based descriptions are likely more common in LLM training data, and hence they may lead to more accurate results than indirectly interpreting actions through sensor events."
  ]
}